  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been a complex and progressive process:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Increased focus on drug-related financial crimes\n- Development of initial reporting requirements\n- Growing international cooperation\n\n3. 1990s Expansion\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established\n- More comprehensive international standards\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Focus on suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stronger emphasis on combating terrorist financing\n- Expanded regulatory scope\n- Increased information sharing\n\n5. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Stricter beneficial ownership disclosure\n- More complex risk-based approaches\n- Global beneficial ownership registries\n- Advanced technological compliance mechanisms\n\n6. Ongoing Trends\n- Continuous regulatory adaptation\n- Increased technological integration\n- More comprehensive international collaboration\n- Greater emphasis on preventing financial crimes\n\nThese legislative developments reflect growing complexity and technological sophistication in financial crime prevention.",
